\begin_layout Subsection*
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Laws of Motion for a Particle:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Stating 
\series bold
three
\series default
 basic laws applying to the motion of a particle, the first being the 
\emph on
law of motion
\emph default
 which summarizes Newton's first two laws as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F=}k\frac{d}{dt}(m\mathbf{v})=km\mathbf{a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is linear momentum, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p=}m\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Choosing units such that 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}=m\mathbf{a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
The second basic law expresses 
\emph on
collinearity
\emph default
 of the interaction of forces as the 
\emph on
law of action and reaction:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Two particles exert interaction forces on one another that are equal in
 magnitude, opposite in sense, and directed along straight line joining
 particles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Finally the third basic law, 
\emph on
law of addition of forces
\emph default
,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}=\mathbf{P}+\mathbf{Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
