\begin_layout Subsection*
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Rigid Body Motion About a Fixed Point:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Rigid-body-motion"

\end_inset

, the base point of the rigid body is assumed to be fixed at the origin
 O of the cartesian system XYZ.
 In calculation of the velocity of a point P that is fixed in the body using
 an inertial reference frame, 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset


\series default
is the absolute velocity of point P and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\omega}$
\end_inset

is the absolute angular velocity of the body.
 Rotation is occurring about the 
\emph on
instantaneous axis of rotation
\emph default
, with the point P having speed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{s}=\omega rsin\theta
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
The velocity of P is of magnitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{s}$
\end_inset

 and is directed along the tangent of the path.
 Therefore it is seen that for the general case of rigid-body rotation about
 a fixed point that, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{\omega\times r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Differentiating with respect to time, the acceleration of P is given as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{\omega\times\dot{r}}+\mathbf{\dot{\omega}\times r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
or noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\dot{r}}=\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, the form,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{\omega\times(\omega\times r)}+\mathbf{\dot{\omega}\times r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Where from the above, the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\omega\times(\omega\times r)}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
centripetal acceleration 
\emph default
(directed towards the instantaneous axis of rotation) with the remaining
 terms being the 
\emph on
tangential acceleration
\emph default
.
\end_layout

