\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Motion of a Particle in a Uniform Gravitational Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
When the only acting force on a particle is a uniform gravitational field,
 particle motion is confined to the plane established from the initial velocity
 vector and the acting gravitational force.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:The-trajectory-of"

\end_inset

 assume the particle is at 
\emph on
O 
\emph default
at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 with a velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{o}$
\end_inset

 directed at angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 from the 
\emph on
x
\emph default
-axis.
 The velocity components of the particle would be,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}(0)=v_{o}cos\gamma
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{y}(0)=v_{0}sin\gamma
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
with the acceleration components being,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{x}=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{y}=-grav.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
From introductory courses, it is known that the velocity components of the
 particle will behave independently, such that,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{x}=v_{0}cos\gamma
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v_{y}=v_{0}sin\gamma-grav.\,t
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Noting constant accelerations and independence of vertical and horizontal
 motion, direct integration can be used to determine position,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=v_{0}t\,cos\gamma
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=v_{0}t\,sin\gamma-\frac{1}{2}grav.\,t^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Where the time to reach a given distance can be found by solving for either
 
\emph on
x 
\emph default
or 
\emph on
y
