By solving the 
\emph on
x-
\emph default
position equation for 
\emph on
t 
\emph default
and substituting into the 
\emph on
y-
\emph default
position equation, the expression for the shape of the travel-parabola is
 given,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=x\,tan\gamma-\frac{grav.\,x^{2}}{2v_{0}^{2}cos^{2}\gamma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
and by differentiating with respect to 
\emph on
x 
\emph default
and setting the result equal to 0,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{v}=\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{grav.}sin\gamma cos\gamma=\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{2grav.}sin2\gamma
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
From the two above equations,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{v}=\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{2grav.}sin^{2}\gamma
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Similarly, using the expressions for both arbitrary 
\emph on
x-
\emph default
position and 
\emph on
x-
\emph default
position of the vertex, the time to reach the vertex can be solved for,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{v}=\frac{v_{0}}{g}sin\gamma
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
where time of flight 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f}=2t_{v}$
\end_inset

 considering a uniform horizontal.
 Also considering a uniform horizontal, the range 
\begin_inset Formula $R=2x_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Case 2 - 
\series medium

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F=F(}t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
If the acting force is only a function of time (not of position or velocity)
 the equation of motion is written as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m\ddot{x}=F_{x}\mathbf{(}t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 for the 
\emph on
x-
\emph default
direction.
 Integration techniques to determine the velocity yield,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v=v_{0}+\frac{1}{m}\int_{0}^{t}F_{x}(\tau)d\tau
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 While another integration results in,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=x_{0}+v_{0}t+\frac{1}{m}\int_{0}^{t}[\int_{0}^{\tau_{2}}F_{x}(\tau_{1})d\tau_{1}]d\tau_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
SEE EXAMPLE 3-2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Case 3 - 
\series medium

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}=F_{x}(x)\mathbf{i}+F_{y}(y)\mathbf{j}+F_{z}(z)\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Again only considering the 
\emph on
x 
\emph default
component of the force,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m\ddot{x}=F_{x}(x)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 By substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{x=v}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{x}=\frac{dv}{dt}=\frac{dv}{dx}\frac{dx}{dt}=v\frac{dv}{dx}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 It is seen that,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
mv\frac{dv}{dx}=F_{x}(x)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and with direct integration,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}m(v^{2}-v_{0}^{2})=\int_{x_{0}}^{x}F_{x}(x)dx
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 A final integration provides,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t=f(x_{0},\,v_{0},\,x)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where a solution is found in the form,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=g(x_{0},\,v_{0},\,t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
SEE EXAMPLE 3-3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Case 4 - 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F=}F_{x}(\dot{x})\mathbf{i}+F_{y}(\dot{y})\mathbf{j}+F_{z}(\dot{z})\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Since each component of the acting force is still independent, the 
\emph on
x-
\emph default
component is only considered,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m\frac{dv}{dt}=F_{x}(v)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Separation of variables provides,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t=m\int_{v_{0}}^{v}\frac{dv}{F_{x}(v)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Where upon solving for the velocity,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v=\frac{dx}{dt}=g(v_{o},\,t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 With a final integration,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=f(x_{0},\,v_{0},\,t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 A similar approach is to use the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{x}=v\,dv/dx$
\end_inset

 within in the equation of motion as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
mv\frac{dv}{dx}=F_{x}(v)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
Integration provides,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m\int_{v_{0}}^{v}\frac{vdv}{F_{x}(v)}=x-x_{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Subtracting 
\emph on
v 
\emph default
from the expression for 
\emph on
t 
\emph default
and the above expression gives the same result,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=f(x_{0},\,v_{0},\,t)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

